course_metadata.title: Digital tools for auditing building as material bank

content_chunks.content: Sustainable built environment is moving towards circularity by several approaches. While design for disassembly principles can be applied for new buildings under design, there seems to be notable reuse potential of various structural and/or building envelope elements stored in existing buildings, considered to be material bank for urban mining. According to 9R circular construction principles, refuse, rethink and reduce is a way to go, followed by renovation. If demolition is inevitable, reuse of components should be preferred. Remanufacture or recycling of building materials from existing buildings becomes an option, if reuse is complicated. Instead of business as usual demolition, existing buildings should be analysed against possible adaptions of functionality as well as various renovation scenario. Pre-demolition auditing should be carried out in order assess reuse potential of its elements or recycling of materials. Digital tools in combination of expert knowledge have proven to be useful approach for several purposes and can be combined to non-destructive assessment methods. The course gives broader background and guides participants step by step towards the circular construction of existing building stock by applying digital tools (software, web-page, digital material database etc) and advanced digital devices. Main typologies and quantity of buildings is introduced in terms of stored building materials and resource efficiency.

Digital auditing technology for circular construction material banks - this course delivers advanced digital tools and methodologies for evaluating existing buildings as material repositories for urban mining and circular economy applications. Technology for building material auditing includes comprehensive pre-demolition assessment tools and non-destructive evaluation methods combined with expert knowledge integration systems. The course introduces adaptability analysis frameworks for assessing building functionality modifications and structural elements performance evaluation for reuse potential determination. Participants gain expertise in digital material database management and expert knowledge integration into digital auditing platforms for comprehensive building stock analysis. The curriculum covers buildings as material banks concepts, element classification systems for reuse applications, and parallel design methodologies for donor building integration into receival building projects. Students develop skills in design for deconstruction processes, elements classification procedures, and digital tool utilization for circular construction implementation. The course prepares professionals to conduct comprehensive building audits, implement circular construction principles using 9R framework, and leverage digital technologies for maximizing material reuse and resource efficiency in existing building stock renovation and adaptation projects.

Existing housing stock in Estonia – typology, materials, technical solutions etc
Adaptility analysis of existing buildings, possible new or additional functionality and changing requirements
Structural elements and performance of existing buildings
Non-destructive assessment methods of technical condition, degradation mechanisms and reuse potential
Introducing digital tools to audit existing buildings

Parallel design for elements from donor building to be used in receival buildings
